(41, 1, 6, 3, 11, 22, 22, 'did eat locusts', 'Dietary Practices of John the Baptist', 'This connection highlights the dietary choices of John the Baptist, who ate locusts, as mentioned in Mark 1:6. Leviticus 11:22 provides a legal framework for the consumption of locusts, indicating their acceptability in the diet of the Israelites.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 6, 38, 13, 4, 4, NULL, 'Prophetic Garments and Authenticity', 'This connection highlights the contrast between John the Baptist''s rough clothing and the future prophets'' shame in wearing deceptive garments. Both passages emphasize the significance of authenticity in prophetic identity.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 6, 40, 3, 4, 4, 'clothed with camel''s hair', 'Connection of John''s Description', 'Both passages emphasize John''s clothing and diet, highlighting his ascetic lifestyle. The similarities in wording and details suggest a shared source or tradition about John the Baptist.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 7, 44, 13, 25, 25, NULL, 'Connection Between John the Baptist Passages', 'Both passages emphasize the humility of John the Baptist in relation to the one coming after him. They share the phrase about being unworthy to unloose the shoes of the one who follows, highlighting John''s acknowledgment of Jesus'' greater authority.', 'parallel', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 7, 42, 3, 16, 16, NULL, 'Connection of John''s Proclamation', 'Both passages emphasize the arrival of one mightier than John, highlighting his humility. The phrase about being unworthy to unloose the latchet of shoes is present in both, reinforcing the theme of John''s role as a forerunner.', 'parallel', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 7, 43, 1, 27, 27, 'the latchet of whose shoes I am not worthy to stoop down and unloose', 'Connection of Humility and Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the speaker''s unworthiness to unloose the latchet of the shoes of someone greater. This connection highlights the recognition of the authority and might of the one coming after.', 'parallel', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 7, 40, 3, 11, 11, 'mightier than I', 'Connection of Baptism and Mightiness', 'Both passages emphasize the mightiness of the one coming after John the Baptist. They highlight John''s humility in relation to this figure, indicating he is unworthy to handle his shoes.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 7, 42, 7, 6, 7, 'I am not worthy', 'Worthy and Unworthy Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of unworthiness in the presence of a mightier figure. John the Baptist expresses his unworthiness regarding Jesus, while the centurion acknowledges his own unworthiness to have Jesus enter his home.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 7, 43, 3, 28, 31, 'mightier than I after me', 'John the Baptist''s Role', 'Both passages emphasize John the Baptist''s role as a forerunner to Christ. In Mark, he acknowledges the mightiness of the one to come, while in John, he reiterates that he is not the Christ but is sent before Him.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 8, 44, 1, 5, 5, NULL, 'Baptism with the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize the transition from water baptism to baptism with the Holy Ghost. This connection highlights the continuity of John''s message and the promise of the Holy Spirit.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 8, 46, 12, 13, 13, 'baptize you with the Holy Ghost', 'Baptism by the Spirit', 'This connection highlights the theme of baptism with the Holy Spirit. Mark 1:8 introduces the concept of being baptized with the Holy Ghost, while 1 Corinthians 12:13 elaborates on this by explaining how all believers are baptized into one body by the Spirit.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 8, 44, 19, 4, 6, 'baptize you with the Holy Ghost', 'Baptism and the Holy Spirit', 'This connection highlights the theme of baptism and the Holy Spirit. Mark 1:8 mentions being baptized with the Holy Ghost, while Acts 19:4-6 describes the Holy Ghost coming upon those baptized in Jesus'' name.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 8, 29, 2, 28, 28, 'baptize you with the Holy Ghost', 'Connection of Spirit and Baptism', 'Both passages emphasize the outpouring of the Spirit. Mark speaks of being baptized with the Holy Ghost, while Joel describes God pouring out His spirit on all flesh.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 8, 26, 36, 25, 27, 'baptize you with the Holy Ghost', 'Connection of Baptism and Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the cleansing and transformation through water and the Spirit. Mark speaks of baptism with the Holy Ghost, while Ezekiel describes being cleansed and receiving a new spirit.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 8, 20, 1, 23, 23, 'baptize you with the Holy Ghost', 'Connection of Spirit and Baptism', 'Both passages emphasize the pouring out of the Spirit. Mark speaks of baptism with the Holy Ghost, while Proverbs mentions pouring out my spirit, suggesting a thematic link between divine empowerment and revelation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 8, 23, 32, 15, 15, 'baptize you with the Holy Ghost', 'Connection of Spirit and Baptism', 'This connection highlights the theme of the spirit being poured out, as seen in both passages. Mark 1:8 speaks of baptism with the Holy Ghost, while Isaiah 32:15 mentions the spirit being poured upon us from on high.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 9, 40, 2, 23, 23, 'Nazareth of Galilee', 'Connection of Nazareth and Baptism', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' connection to Nazareth. Mark mentions Jesus coming from Nazareth, while Matthew highlights his dwelling there, fulfilling prophecy.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 9, 40, 3, 13, 17, 'Jesus came from Nazareth of Galilee', 'Connection of Jesus'' Baptism', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' baptism by John. They describe the act of coming from Galilee to Jordan, highlighting the significance of this event in Jesus'' ministry.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 9, 42, 3, 21, 22, 'was baptized of John in Jordan', 'Baptism of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the event of Jesus'' baptism. Mark 1:9 introduces the baptism, while Luke 3:21-22 elaborates on the moment, including the descent of the Holy Spirit.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 10, 42, 3, 22, 22, 'the Spirit like a dove descending upon him', 'Baptism and Holy Spirit Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the descent of the Spirit like a dove during Jesus'' baptism. This connection highlights the divine affirmation of Jesus as God''s Son.', 'parallel', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 10, 43, 1, 31, 34, 'the Spirit like a dove descending', 'Connection of Spirit Descending', 'Both passages emphasize the Spirit descending like a dove, highlighting the divine confirmation of Jesus'' identity. Mark describes the event at Jesus'' baptism, while John recounts it as a testimony of recognition.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 10, 23, 42, 1, 1, 'the Spirit like a dove descending upon him', 'Connection of Spirit and Servant', 'This connection highlights the descent of the Spirit in Mark 1:10 and the mention of the Spirit in Isaiah 42:1. Both passages emphasize the role of the Spirit in empowering God''s chosen servant.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 10, 23, 64, 1, 1, 'heavens opened', 'Heavens Opened and Divine Presence', 'This connection highlights the theme of the heavens being opened to reveal God''s presence. In Mark, the heavens are opened as the Spirit descends, while Isaiah expresses a longing for the heavens to be torn open for God''s coming down.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 10, 40, 3, 16, 16, NULL, 'Baptism and Spirit''s Descent', 'Both passages emphasize the moment of Jesus'' baptism and the descent of the Spirit like a dove. The imagery of the heavens opening and the Spirit descending is consistent in both accounts, highlighting a significant event in Jesus'' ministry.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 11, 23, 42, 1, 1, 'in whom I am well pleased', 'Divine Approval of the Servant', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of divine approval, as seen in the phrases ''my beloved Son'' and ''mine elect, in whom my soul delighteth.'' This connection highlights the significance of God''s endorsement of His chosen servant.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
